  "prompt": "Which one is grammatically correct: pick up someone at the airport or from the airport?",
  "response": "Both phrases can be grammatically correct, but they suggest slightly different meanings. \n\n- \"Pick up someone at the airport\" typically means to meet and collect someone at the location of the airport.\n- \"Pick up someone from the airport\" suggests that you are collecting someone who is arriving at the airport and bringing them away from there.\n\nIn most contexts, \"pick up someone at the airport\" is commonly used when referring to the action of meeting them there. However, both are understood and can be used interchangeably in casual conversation.",
